\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a growing interest in using payments for ecosystem services to
 promote land conservation activities that can influence water quality.
 For instance, forested land near rivers is believed to provide benefits
 for both water quality and flow patterns.
 One of the big challenges policy makers face in adopting such programs
 is the considerable degree of uncertainty regarding the precise level of
 environmental services provided by any given parcel of land.
 Moreover, since land conversion is an on-going process that is only partially
 reversible and any payments made today are unrecoverable, regulators face
 a timing problem.
 Is it better to implement a payment for ecosystem services plan today or
 wait for better information? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The answer to this question depends on the relationship between the likelihood
 of land conversion and the services provided by parcels.
 For example, a positive correlation between the unknown level of environmental
 benefits from keeping a specific parcel forested and the economic benefits
 from converting that parcel to alternate uses increases both the value
 of waiting for more information to target the payments more closely and
 the cost of waiting since the land converted in the interim is likely to
 be especially environmentally valuable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I develop a two period model analytical model to explore these relationships.
 A regulator is considering implementing a payment-for-ecosystem-services
 (PES) plan that would cover a set of individual parcels.
 The parcels differ in both the economic value of conversion and the environment
al service value provided by conserving them.
 In the first period, only the mean and variance of environmental service
 value across all parcels is known by either party.
 Landowners know their own economic value and both landowners and regulators
 know the mean and variance of economic value.
 Regulators can implement a PES plan in the first period by offering landowners
 a payment in exchange for conserving their land.
 Landowners can choose to accept this offer or to convert their land, thus
 eliminating the ecosystem service it provides.
 In the second period, both regulators and landowners learn additional informati
on about the ecosystem services provided by individual parcels.
 This allows the regulator to make differentiated PES offers to each individual
 landowner.
 To the extent that there is correlation between the economic and ecosystem
 service values of individual parcels, the landownerâ€™s private information
 about their own economic value provides them with private information about
 the likely PES offer they will receive in the second period and thus influences
 their decision about whether to accept payment or convert their land in
 period 1.
 
\end_layout

