\begin_layout Itemize
Current model assumes that regulator cares about the sum of conversion value
 and ecosystem service value.
 Extensions include weighting ecosystem service and conversion values differentl
y, introducing a function mapping landowner benefit from conversion into
 regulator benefit (property tax revenue, economic activity multiplier).
 While it is almost certainly true that regulators don't weight the two
 equally, I'd need a market imperfection story to argue that the first-best
 isn't weighting them equally.
 (E.g.
 land markets have imperfections that mean that the value to the landowner
 does not equal the social value of conversion).
 Since this is not central to the story, it's probably not worth doing.
 Another possibility is to think about an environmental regulator with a
 fixed budget but again, I lose any claim to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimality
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the resulting policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Current model assumes that funds are costless so transfers don't matter.
 It would be natural to include some type of deadweight loss from taxation
 that would make me want to limit payments.
 We know this will lead to smaller payment levels and a less than optimal
 amount of land being conserved.
 Might be something interesting in how it affects the dynamic decision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Risk aversion.
 Everyone is risk neutral right now.
 Risk aversion should make everyone want to take the sure thing today over
 waiting so will definitely affect the dynamic decision.
 It will also affect the regulators' choices in the next period and make
 the math more complicated.
 We'll be forced to numerical simulation earlier in the math but it shouldn't
 make a huge difference in the time needed to compute things.
\end_layout

